Issues.Body:
### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

common, compiler-cli, compiler, core

### Description

I was hoping to propose introducing a new ChangeDetectionStrategy.DeepProxy at the Angular level.

I have had some success deeply injecting Proxy classes into my component objects in conjunction with the OnPush change detection strategy:
```
constructor(private _cdr: ChangeDetectorRef) {
    injectChangeDetectionProxies(this, this._cdr);
}
```

The injectChangeDetectionProxies function effectively traverses the component object tree and injects Proxy classes on every object in order to detect changes to any of their properties and automatically call cdr.markForCheck() accordingly so that the interface updates as expected.

Now the above is obviously a bit of overkill because I only really need to setup Proxy objects on the parents of values that are used in the template. However, this seems to work quite well and quicky so far for detecting changes and seems to avoid the necessity of changing everything to use immutable types or having to rewrite all my components to use Signals (or any of the other workarounds).

### Proposed solution

My proposed solution would be to move a similar injectChangeDetectionProxies function inside angular where it could be activated for any component behind a new ChangeDetectionStrategy.DeepProxy change detection strategy flag.

And furthermore, instead of calling cdr.markForCheck() these proxies could instead enqueue/map their property name + new value changes where they could be later be applied during the change cycle.

This would have several advantages over existing change detection strategies:
(1) The expensive tree traversal to detect changes no longer becomes necessary at all and could be avoided completely. Instead of calling cdr.markForCheck() the Proxy could immediately queue/map the exact parameter name and new value of the change that needs to take place. Later, what was previously the change detection cycle could instead traverse just the exact list of changes that need to take place and apply them.
(2) Users would not have to refactor their code to use immutable structures, make manual calls to cdr.markForCheck(), use Signals, etc. etc. in order to take advantage of the performance boost.
(3) Proxied objects are theoretically meant to be somewhat transparent. So in theory, anything that doesn't properly Proxy could potentially be flagged as a bug in JavaScript and bumped upstream to the language developers.

The Angular developers are also in a unique position to make sure that these Proxy's only get applied to objects/properties used in the template for even more targeted updates.

That isn't to say that there aren't also some challenges to using Proxy objects everywhere:
(1) Map (and possibly File objects) don't seem to like being proxied very much. And possibly others. These sorts of issues could maybe be bumped upstream but would maybe require workarounds or warnings in the documentation in the short term.
(2) Circular references in the Component's object tree (such as parent references) are something to be careful about (but were actually relatively easy to work around by marking already proxied objects).
(3) Proxing of the Component tree incurs some extra cost at load time in exchange for the improved speed later at runtime.
(4) And probably some others surprises I haven't thought of.

For convenience, here is some of my working implementation to highlight the basic idea:
```
const isProxy = Symbol("isProxy");
const isProxying = Symbol("isProxying");

type HandlerType = {
    set: (target: object, path: PropertyKey[], value: any, receiver: any)=>void,
    deleteProperty: (target: object, path: PropertyKey[]) => void, 
}

function isInstance(obj: any, cls: any): boolean {
  try {
    return obj instanceof cls;
  } catch {
    return false;
  }
}

function isProxyable(obj: any): boolean {
  return (obj !== undefined && obj !== null && typeof obj === "object" &&
    !obj[isProxy] && !(isInstance(obj, Map) && !(isInstance(obj, File))));
}

export function createDeepProxy(target: any, handler: HandlerType, skipKeys: PropertyKey[], key: PropertyKey): any {
    function makeHandler(path: PropertyKey[]) {
      return {
        set(target: object, key: PropertyKey, value: any, receiver: any) {
          if (!(key as string).startsWith("_") && !skipKeys.includes(key as string) && isProxyable(value)) {
            value = proxify(value, [...path, key], skipKeys);
          }
          target[key] = value;
          
          if (handler.set) {
            handler.set(target, [...path, key], value, receiver);
          }
          return true;
        },
        get(target: object, key: PropertyKey) {
          // This allows us to check if this object has already been proxied.
          // From: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/36372611/how-to-test-if-an-object-is-a-proxy
          if (key == isProxy) {
            return true;
          }
          return target[key];
        },
        deleteProperty(target: object, key: PropertyKey) {
          if (Reflect.has(target, key)) {
            const deleted = Reflect.deleteProperty(target, key);
            if (deleted && handler.deleteProperty) {
              handler.deleteProperty(target, [...path, key]);
            }
            return deleted;
          }
          // Returning true to avoid messages like:
          // ERROR TypeError: 'deleteProperty' on proxy: trap returned falsish for property 'fromTime'
          // Deleting a property that doesn't exist does not normally generate an error.
          // So this shouldn't generate one either (IMHO).
          return true;
        }
      }
    }
    
    function proxify(obj: any, path: PropertyKey[], skipKeys: PropertyKey[]): any {
      // These initial checks are largely to avoid re-proxifying an object that
      // has already been proxified. This happened for example
      // in our "tree" component where it recursively passed the proxy tree
      // down the component tree.
      if (!isProxyable(obj)) {
        return obj;
      }
      if (obj[isProxying]) {
        console.warn(`Change detection proxy loop detected: ${path.join(",")}`);
        return obj;
      }

      // This must be done first so it is already there when we descend into the children.
      obj[isProxying] = true;
      for (const key of Object.getOwnPropertyNames(obj)) {
        // Avoid recursion on particular properties (UntypedFormGroup for example)
        if (key.startsWith("_") || skipKeys.includes(key)) {
          continue;
        }
        //console.log([...path, key]);
        if (obj[key] != null && typeof obj[key] === 'object') {
          const descriptor = Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(obj, key);
          // If the descriptor doesn't have a getter then it is likely a regular data object
          // and we can set the properties freely.
          // If the descriptor has a getter then it likely uses getters/setters so we have to
          // make sure there is also a setter we can use to proxify it. Without a setter
          // there is nothing we can proxify.
          if (descriptor?.get === undefined) {
            obj[key] = proxify(obj[key], [...path, key], skipKeys);
          } else if (descriptor.set !== undefined) {
            console.log("setter proxying is not implemented");
          }
        }
      }
      delete obj[isProxying];
      return new Proxy(obj, makeHandler(path));
    }
  
    return proxify(target, [key], skipKeys);
  }

  function getDetectingProxy(target: any, cdr: ChangeDetectorRef, skipKeys: PropertyKey[], key: string): any {
    return createDeepProxy(target, {
      set() {
        //console.log('set', path.join('.'));
        cdr.markForCheck();
      },
      deleteProperty() {
        //console.log('delete', path.join('.'));
        cdr.markForCheck();
      }
    }, skipKeys, key);
  }
```

My apologies as the above code could use a bunch of cleanup.

The usage of this would be something like:
`const proxiedThis = getDetectingProxy(this, this._cdr);`

The following stack overflow is a good starting point for how to write a deep proxy:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/43177855/how-to-create-a-deep-proxy-aka-proxy-membrane

I'd be happy to answer any questions or discuss this further.

### Alternatives considered

I have also had success chaining getters/setters to achieve a similar effect but the Proxy class seems like a better fit in terms of what it was designed to do.

